content:
Nice clash, but it's not great for Shortest mode currently due to a lack of similar coverage between tests and validators.

I got 100% on test cases in Shortest mode, but then 75% on validators because I'd taken advantage of the trend that the string we want to extract was always before the last "." in the url for all the test cases, but then Validator "Educational Resources" has a "." in some of the later url for the 'djangoproject' line, messing up this trick.

It would be best to add another test/validator pair where the test now has a similar url e.g.:
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASP.NET_Core" -> wikipedia

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: It's unique, it was fun to solve.

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: I like the contribution. It looks well made.

Be careful on the wording : https://www.semrush.com/blog/top-level-domains/

Domain name is "linkedin.com"

Second-level domain is "linkedin"

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: Good Clash. Very clear and apparent description, good test-cases and overall a neat challenge for string manipulation. Simulates a real-world scenario too. After coding a solution, I don't see why you wouldn't be able to adjust it and create a real program for this sort of work!

Nice Job @FruGosky!

Interesting looking CoC. 

I would advise taking the two last lines out of CONSTRAINTS and putting them int the STATEMENT... as they aren't really constraints like the first line is.

Apart from that I really like your clash. It's fun and a good one.
Thanks for support! I made a correction
Clearly too early for your ✅ again…
Thanks, really good point! I have made the correction.

Output
* Please change "Line by line" to "[[N]] lines".

Constraints
* Please change 100 to 10 to better reflect the actual cases.

Cases
* Best if you can correct the typos in the name of "Contry-Specyfic" test (both words are spelled wrong).

* Please revise "Long url" validator - The input should begin with "https://".

* The country-specific test is the only case where length of "xx" (in the ".xx" part) is 2 (otherwise it's all 3 as in .com or .org). Please revise at least one other **validator** to cover a similar situation.

Thanks.

P.S. I don't know why "http" is mentioned in Goal section when it isn't covered in any cases at all.

Thanks for all the points, every one of them has been corrected! I hope that now everything is correct and that you liked the idea of my challenge. If you find something different, feel free to write about it and I will be happy to correct it

Thank you.

One of the issues has not been addressed yet, and that is the length of the .xx part issue. If you look at the names of the cases, you'll see some small words which say "TEST" and "VALIDATOR". So, what you should do now is to add at least one url to one of the **validators** where the url would contain a ".xx" part of length 2.

Thanks again.
